<h1><a class='u' href='#___top' title='click to go to top of document'
name="NAME"
>NAME <img alt='^' src='http://st.pimg.net/tucs/img/up.gif'></a></h1>

<p>POE - portable multitasking and networking framework for any event loop</p>

<h1><a class='u' href='#___top' title='click to go to top of document'
name="SYNOPSIS"
>SYNOPSIS <img alt='^' src='http://st.pimg.net/tucs/img/up.gif'></a></h1>

<pre class="sh_perl">  #!/usr/bin/perl -w
  use strict;

  use POE;  # Auto-includes POE::Kernel and POE::Session.

  sub handler_start {
    my ($kernel, $heap, $session) = @_[KERNEL, HEAP, SESSION];
    print &#34;Session &#34;, $session-&#62;ID, &#34; has started.\n&#34;;
    $heap-&#62;{count} = 0;
    $kernel-&#62;yield(&#39;increment&#39;);
  }

  sub handler_increment {
    my ($kernel, $heap, $session) = @_[KERNEL, HEAP, SESSION];
    print &#34;Session &#34;, $session-&#62;ID, &#34; counted to &#34;, ++$heap-&#62;{count}, &#34;.\n&#34;;
    $kernel-&#62;yield(&#39;increment&#39;) if $heap-&#62;{count} &#60; 10;
  }

  sub handler_stop {
    print &#34;Session &#34;, $_[SESSION]-&#62;ID, &#34; has stopped.\n&#34;;
  }

  for (1..10) {
    POE::Session-&#62;create(
      inline_states =&#62; {
        _start    =&#62; \&#38;handler_start,
        increment =&#62; \&#38;handler_increment,
        _stop     =&#62; \&#38;handler_stop,
      }
    );
  }

  POE::Kernel-&#62;run();
  exit;</pre>

<h1><a class='u' href='#___top' title='click to go to top of document'
name="DESCRIPTION"
>DESCRIPTION <img alt='^' src='http://st.pimg.net/tucs/img/up.gif'></a></h1>

<p>POE is a framework for cooperative, event driven multitasking and networking in Perl. Other languages have similar frameworks. Python has Twisted. TCL has &#34;the event loop&#34;.</p>

<p>POE provides a unified interface for several other event loops, including select(), <a href="/perldoc?IO%3A%3APoll" class="podlinkpod"
>IO::Poll</a>, <a href="/perldoc?Glib" class="podlinkpod"
>Glib</a>, <a href="/perldoc?Gtk" class="podlinkpod"
>Gtk</a>, <a href="/perldoc?Tk" class="podlinkpod"
>Tk</a>, <a href="/perldoc?Wx" class="podlinkpod"
>Wx</a>, and <a href="/perldoc?Gtk2" class="podlinkpod"
>Gtk2</a>. Many of these event loop interfaces were written by others, with the help of POE::Test::Loops. They may be found on the CPAN.</p>

<p>POE achieves its its high degree of portability to different operating systems and Perl versions by being written entirely in Perl. CPAN hosts optional XS modules for POE if speed is more desirable than portability.</p>

<p>POE is designed in layers. Each layer builds atop the lower level ones. Programs are free to use POE at any level of abstraction, and different levels can be mixed and matched seamlessly within a single program. Remember, though, that higher-level abstractions often require more resources than lower-level ones. The conveniences they provide are not free.</p>

<p>POE&#39;s bundled abstraction layers are the tip of a growing iceberg. <a href="/perldoc?Sprocket" class="podlinkpod"
>Sprocket</a>, <a href="/perldoc?POE%3A%3AStage" class="podlinkpod"
>POE::Stage</a>, and other CPAN distributions build upon this work. You&#39;re encouraged to look around.</p>

<p>No matter how high you go, though, it all boils down to calls to <a href="/~rcaputo/POE-1.352/lib/POE/Kernel.pm" class="podlinkpod"
>POE::Kernel</a>. So your down-to-earth code can easily cooperate with stratospheric systems.</p>

<h2><a class='u' href='#___top' title='click to go to top of document'
name="Layer_1:_Kernel_and_Sessions"
>Layer 1: Kernel and Sessions</a></h2>

<p>The lowest public layer is comprised of <a href="/~rcaputo/POE-1.352/lib/POE/Kernel.pm" class="podlinkpod"
>POE::Kernel</a>, <a href="/~rcaputo/POE-1.352/lib/POE/Session.pm" class="podlinkpod"
>POE::Session</a>, and other session types.</p>

<p><a href="/~rcaputo/POE-1.352/lib/POE/Kernel.pm" class="podlinkpod"
>POE::Kernel</a> does most of the heavy lifting. It provides a portable interface for filehandle activity detection, multiple alarms and other timers, signal handling, and other less-common features.</p>

<p><a href="/~rcaputo/POE-1.352/lib/POE/Session.pm" class="podlinkpod"
>POE::Session</a> and derived classes encapsulate the notion of an event driven task. They also customize event dispatch to a particular calling convention. <a href="/~rcaputo/POE-1.352/lib/POE/NFA.pm" class="podlinkpod"
>POE::NFA</a>, for example, is more of a proper state machine. The CPAN has several other kinds of sessions.</p>

<p>Everything ultimately builds on these classes or the concepts they implement. If you&#39;re short on time, the things to read besides this are <a href="/~rcaputo/POE-1.352/lib/POE/Kernel.pm" class="podlinkpod"
>POE::Kernel</a> and <a href="/~rcaputo/POE-1.352/lib/POE/Session.pm" class="podlinkpod"
>POE::Session</a>.</p>

<h2><a class='u' href='#___top' title='click to go to top of document'
name="Layer_2:_Wheels,_Filters,_and_Drivers"
>Layer 2: Wheels, Filters, and Drivers</a></h2>

<p>POE::Wheel objects are dynamic mix-ins for POE::Session instances. These &#34;wheels&#34; perform very common, generic tasks in a highly reusable and customizable way. <a href="/~rcaputo/POE-1.352/lib/POE/Wheel/ReadWrite.pm" class="podlinkpod"
>POE::Wheel::ReadWrite</a>, for example, implements non-blocking buffered I/O. Nearly everybody needs this, so why require people to reinvent it all the time?</p>

<p><a href="/~rcaputo/POE-1.352/lib/POE/Filter.pm" class="podlinkpod"
>POE::Filter</a> objects customize wheels in a modular way. Filters act as I/O layers, turning raw streams into structured data, and serializing structures into something suitable for streams. The CPAN also has several of these.</p>

<p>Drivers are where the wheels meet the road. In this case, the road is some type of file handle. Drivers do the actual reading and writing in a standard way so wheels don&#39;t need to know the difference between send() and syswrite().</p>

<p><a href="/~rcaputo/POE-1.352/lib/POE/Driver.pm" class="podlinkpod"
>POE::Driver</a> objects get relatively short shrift because very few are needed. The most common driver, <a href="/~rcaputo/POE-1.352/lib/POE/Driver/SysRW.pm" class="podlinkpod"
>POE::Driver::SysRW</a> is ubiquitous and also the default, so most people will never need to specify one.</p>

<h2><a class='u' href='#___top' title='click to go to top of document'
name="Layer_3:_Components"
>Layer 3: Components</a></h2>

<p><a href="/~rcaputo/POE-1.352/lib/POE/Component.pm" class="podlinkpod"
>POE::Component</a> classes are essentially Perl classes that use POE to perform tasks in a non-blocking or cooperative way. This is a very broad definition, and POE components are all over the abstraction map.</p>

<p>Many components, such as <a href="/perldoc?POE%3A%3AComponent%3A%3AServer%3A%3ASMTP" class="podlinkpod"
>POE::Component::Server::SMTP</a>, encapsulate the generic details of an entire application. Others perform rather narrow tasks, such as <a href="/perldoc?POE%3A%3AComponent%3A%3ADirWatch%3A%3AObject" class="podlinkpod"
>POE::Component::DirWatch::Object</a>.</p>

<p>POE components are often just plain Perl objects. The previously mentioned <a href="/perldoc?POE%3A%3AComponent%3A%3ADirWatch%3A%3AObject" class="podlinkpod"
>POE::Component::DirWatch::Object</a> uses <a href="/perldoc?Moose" class="podlinkpod"
>Moose</a>. Other object and meta-object frameworks are compatible.</p>

<p>Also of interest is <a href="/perldoc?POE%3A%3AComponent%3A%3AGeneric" class="podlinkpod"
>POE::Component::Generic</a>, which is allows you to create a POE component from nearly nearly any blocking module.</p>

<p>There are quite a lot of components on the CPAN. <a href="http://search.cpan.org/search?query=poe+component&#38;mode=all" class="podlinkurl"
>http://search.cpan.org/search?query=poe+component&#38;mode=all</a></p>

<h2><a class='u' href='#___top' title='click to go to top of document'
name="Layer_4_and_Beyond:_Frameworks_and_Object_Metaphors"
>Layer 4 and Beyond: Frameworks and Object Metaphors</a></h2>

<p>It&#39;s possible to abstract POE entirely behind a different framework. In fact we encourage people to write domain-specific abstractions that entirely hide POE if necessary. The nice thing here is that even at these high levels of abstraction, things will continue to interoperate all the way down to layer 1.</p>

<p>Two examples of ultra-high level abstraction are <a href="/perldoc?Sprocket" class="podlinkpod"
>Sprocket</a>, a networking framework that does its own thing, and <a href="/perldoc?POE%3A%3AStage" class="podlinkpod"
>POE::Stage</a>, which is POE&#39;s creator&#39;s attempt to formalize and standardize POE components.</p>

<p>It is also possible to communicate between POE processes. This is called IKC, for <i>Inter-Kernel Communication</i>. There are a few IKC components on the CPAN (<a href="http://search.cpan.org/search?query=IKC&#38;mode=all" class="podlinkurl"
>http://search.cpan.org/search?query=IKC&#38;mode=all</a>), notably <a href="/perldoc?POE%3A%3AComponent%3A%3AIKC" class="podlinkpod"
>POE::Component::IKC</a> and <a href="/perldoc?POE%3A%3ATIKC" class="podlinkpod"
>POE::TIKC</a>.</p>

<h2><a class='u' href='#___top' title='click to go to top of document'
name="Layer_0:_POE&#39;s_Internals"
>Layer 0: POE&#39;s Internals</a></h2>

<p>POE&#39;s layered architecture continues below the surface. POE&#39;s guts are broken into specific <a href="/~rcaputo/POE-1.352/lib/POE/Loop.pm" class="podlinkpod"
>POE::Loop</a> classes for each event loop it supports. Internals are divided up by type, giving <a href="/~rcaputo/POE-1.352/lib/POE/Resource.pm" class="podlinkpod"
>POE::Resource</a> classes for Aliases, Controls, Events, Extrefs, FileHandles, SIDs, Sessions and Signals.</p>

<p>POE::Kernel&#39;s APIs are extensible through POE::API mix-in classes. Some brave souls have even published new APIs on CPAN, such as <a href="/perldoc?POE%3A%3AAPI%3A%3APeek" class="podlinkpod"
>POE::API::Peek</a> (which gives you access to some of the internal <a href="/~rcaputo/POE-1.352/lib/POE/Resource.pm" class="podlinkpod"
>POE::Resource</a> methods).</p>

<p>By design, it&#39;s possible to implement new <a href="/~rcaputo/POE-1.352/lib/POE/Kernel.pm" class="podlinkpod"
>POE::Kernel</a> guts by creating another <a href="/~rcaputo/POE-1.352/lib/POE/Resource.pm" class="podlinkpod"
>POE::Resource</a> class. One can then expose the functionality with a new POE::API mix-in.</p>

<h1><a class='u' href='#___top' title='click to go to top of document'
name="DOCUMENTATION_ROADMAP"
>DOCUMENTATION ROADMAP <img alt='^' src='http://st.pimg.net/tucs/img/up.gif'></a></h1>

<p>You&#39;re reading the main POE documentation. It&#39;s the general entry point to the world of POE. You already know this, however, so let&#39;s talk about something more interesting.</p>

<h2><a class='u' href='#___top' title='click to go to top of document'
name="Basic_Features"
>Basic Features</a></h2>

<p>POE&#39;s basic features are documented mainly in <a href="/~rcaputo/POE-1.352/lib/POE/Kernel.pm" class="podlinkpod"
>POE::Kernel</a> and <a href="/~rcaputo/POE-1.352/lib/POE/Session.pm" class="podlinkpod"
>POE::Session</a>. Methods are documented in the classes that implement them. Broader concepts are covered in the most appropriate class, and sometimes they are divided among classes that share in their implementation.</p>

<h2><a class='u' href='#___top' title='click to go to top of document'
name="Basic_Usage"
>Basic Usage</a></h2>

<p>Basic usage, even for POE.pm, is documented in <a href="/~rcaputo/POE-1.352/lib/POE/Kernel.pm" class="podlinkpod"
>POE::Kernel</a>. That&#39;s where most of POE&#39;s work is done, and POE.pm is little more than a class loader.</p>

<h2><a class='u' href='#___top' title='click to go to top of document'
name="@_[KERNEL,_HEAP,_etc.]"
>@_[KERNEL, HEAP, etc.]</a></h2>

<p>Event handler calling conventions, that weird <code>@_[KERNEL, HEAP]</code> stuff, is documented in <a href="/~rcaputo/POE-1.352/lib/POE/Session.pm" class="podlinkpod"
>POE::Session</a>. That&#39;s because POE::Session implements the calling convention, and other session types often do it differently.</p>

<h2><a class='u' href='#___top' title='click to go to top of document'
name="Base_Classes_Document_Common_Features"
>Base Classes Document Common Features</a></h2>

<p>The <a href="/~rcaputo/POE-1.352/lib/POE/Wheel.pm" class="podlinkpod"
>POE::Wheel</a>, <a href="/~rcaputo/POE-1.352/lib/POE/Driver.pm" class="podlinkpod"
>POE::Driver</a>, <a href="/~rcaputo/POE-1.352/lib/POE/Filter.pm" class="podlinkpod"
>POE::Filter</a>, and <a href="/~rcaputo/POE-1.352/lib/POE/Component.pm" class="podlinkpod"
>POE::Component</a> base classes describe what&#39;s common among each class. It&#39;s a good idea to at least skim the base class documentation since the subclasses tend not to rehash the common things.</p>

<p><a href="/~rcaputo/POE-1.352/lib/POE/Queue.pm" class="podlinkpod"
>POE::Queue</a>, <a href="/~rcaputo/POE-1.352/lib/POE/Resource.pm" class="podlinkpod"
>POE::Resource</a>, and <a href="/~rcaputo/POE-1.352/lib/POE/Loop.pm" class="podlinkpod"
>POE::Loop</a> document the concepts and sometimes the standard interfaces behind multiple subclasses. You&#39;re encouraged to have a look.</p>

<h2><a class='u' href='#___top' title='click to go to top of document'
name="Helper_Classes"
>Helper Classes</a></h2>

<p>POE includes some helper classes for portability. <a href="/~rcaputo/POE-1.352/lib/POE/Pipe.pm" class="podlinkpod"
>POE::Pipe</a>, and its subclasses <a href="/~rcaputo/POE-1.352/lib/POE/Pipe/OneWay.pm" class="podlinkpod"
>POE::Pipe::OneWay</a> and <a href="/~rcaputo/POE-1.352/lib/POE/Pipe/TwoWay.pm" class="podlinkpod"
>POE::Pipe::TwoWay</a> are portable pipes.</p>

<h2><a class='u' href='#___top' title='click to go to top of document'
name="Event_Loop_Bridges"
>Event Loop Bridges</a></h2>

<p><a href="/~rcaputo/POE-1.352/lib/POE/Loop.pm" class="podlinkpod"
>POE::Loop</a> documents and specifies the interface for all of POE&#39;s event loop bridges. The individual classes may document specific details, but generally they adhere to the spec strongly enough that they don&#39;t need to.</p>

<p>Many of the existing <a href="/~rcaputo/POE-1.352/lib/POE/Loop.pm" class="podlinkpod"
>POE::Loop</a> bridges provided in POE&#39;s base distribution will move out to separate distributions shortly. The documentation will probably remain the same, however.</p>

<h2><a class='u' href='#___top' title='click to go to top of document'
name="POE::Queue_and_POE::Queue::Array"
>POE::Queue and POE::Queue::Array</a></h2>

<p>POE&#39;s event queue is basically a priority heap implemented as an ordered array. <a href="/~rcaputo/POE-1.352/lib/POE/Queue.pm" class="podlinkpod"
>POE::Queue</a> documents the standard interface for POE event queues, and <a href="/~rcaputo/POE-1.352/lib/POE/Queue/Array.pm" class="podlinkpod"
>POE::Queue::Array</a> implements the ordered array queue. Tony Cook has released <a href="/perldoc?POE%3A%3AXS%3A%3AQueue%3A%3AArray" class="podlinkpod"
>POE::XS::Queue::Array</a>, which is a drop-in C replacement for <a href="/~rcaputo/POE-1.352/lib/POE/Queue/Array.pm" class="podlinkpod"
>POE::Queue::Array</a>. You might give it a try if you need more performance. POE&#39;s event queue is some of the hottest code in the system.</p>

